http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Actor.label: actor
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Actor.comment: An actor or actress is a person who acts in a dramatic production and who works in film, television, theatre, or radio in that capacity.

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Agent.label: agent
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Agent.comment: Analogous to a foaf:Agent, an agent is an entity that acts. This is intended to be the super class of Person and Organisation.

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/BroadcastNet.label: broadcast network
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/BroadcastNet.comment: A broadcast network is an organization, such as a corporation or other association, that provides live or recorded content, such as movies, newscasts, sports, and public affairs programs for broadcast over a group of radio or television stations. (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broadcast_network - 28/03/2011)

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Broadcaster.label: broadcaster
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Broadcaster.comment: A broadcaster is an organisation responsible for the production of radio or television programs and/or their transmission. (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broadcaster - 28/03/2011)

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Building.label: building
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Building.comment: Building is defined as a Civil Engineering structure such as a house, worship center, factory etc. that has a foundation, wall, roof etc. that protect human being and their properties from direct harsh effect of weather like rain, wind, sun etc. (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Building).

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/CareerStatio.label: career station
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/CareerStatio.comment: this class marks a career step in the life of a person, e.g. a soccer player, holding information on the time span, matches and goals he or she achieved at a certain club

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/City.label: city
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/City.comment: a relatively large and permanent settlement, particularly a large urban settlement

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Community.label: Community
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Community.comment: A community is a group of living organisms, people, plants or animals that live in a common environment.

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Magazine.label: magazine
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Magazine.comment: Magazines, periodicals, glossies or serials are publications, generally published on a regular schedule, containing a variety of articles. They are generally financed by advertising, by a purchase price, by pre-paid magazine subscriptions, or all three.

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/MountainRang.label: mountain range
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/MountainRang.comment: a chain of mountains bordered by highlands or separated from other mountains by passes or valleys.

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Newspaper.label: newspaper
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Newspaper.comment: A newspaper is a regularly scheduled publication containing news of current events, informative articles, diverse features and advertising. It usually is printed on relatively inexpensive, low-grade paper such as newsprint.

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Novel.label: novel
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Novel.comment: A book of long narrative in literary prose

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Organ.label: organ
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Organ.comment: All types and sizes of organs

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/PopulatedPla.label: populated place
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/PopulatedPla.comment: As defined by the United States Geological Survey, a populated place is a place or area with clustered or scattered buildings and a permanent human population (city, settlement, town, or village) referenced with geographic coordinates (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Populated_place).

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Project.label: project
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Project.comment: A project is a temporary endeavor undertaken to achieve defined objectives.

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Province.label: province
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Province.comment: An administrative body governing a territorial unity on the intermediate level, between local and national level

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/RadioStation.label: radio station
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/RadioStation.comment: A radio station has one line up. For instance the radio station BBC Radio 1. Not to be confused with the broadcasting network BBC, which has many radio stations.

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Species.label: species
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Species.comment: A category in the rating system

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/SportsLeague.label: sports league
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/SportsLeague.comment: A group of sports teams or individual athletes that compete against each other in a specific sport.

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Station.label: station
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Station.comment: Public transport station (eg. railway station, metro station, bus station).

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Taxon.label: taxonomic group
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Taxon.comment: a category within a classification system for Species

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Work.label: work
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Work.comment: Item on which time has been spent for its realisation. Actor can be a human on not (machine, insects, nature...)

http://dbpedia.org/ontology/WrittenWork.label: written work
http://dbpedia.org/ontology/WrittenWork.comment: Written work is any text written to read it (e.g.: books, newspaper, articles)
